    /* Artikel No 3 */
    'isi3' => '<p>Quoted from the Indonesian Wikipedia</p>
    <p><strong>Javanese tamarind</strong>, <strong>acid</strong> or <strong>tamarind</strong> is a kind of fruit that tastes sour; commonly used as a mixture of spices in many Indonesian dishes as a flavoring or a sour taste enhancer in foods, for example in sour vegetables. Tamarind is also used to mix traditional herbs sold by mobile herbalists, usually women carrying baskets with bottles filled with various herbs (jamu carrying).</p>
    <p>Javanese acid is produced by <a href="https://id.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tree">tree</a> with scientific name <strong><em>Tamarindus indica</em></strong >, which includes <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Familia">tribes</a> Fabaceae (Leguminosae). <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Species">Species</a> this is the only member of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genus" >surname</a> <em>Tamarindus</em>. Other names for tamarind are tamarind (<a href="https://id.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bahasa_Malay">Mly.</a>), <em>asem</em> (<a href="https ://id.wikipedia.org/wiki/Java_Language">Jw.</a>, <a href="https://id.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sunda_Bahasa">Sd.</a>), < em>accem</em> (<a href="https://id.wikipedia.org/wiki/Language_Madura">Md.</a>), <em>asang java</em>, <em>asang jawi</em> (multiple languages ​​at <a href="https://id.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sulawesi">Sulawesi</a>) and others. Also <em>sampalok</em>, <em>kalamagi</em> (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philippines">Tagalog</a>), <em>magyee </em> (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Burma">Burma</a>), <em>ma-kham</em> (<a href="https: //id.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thailand">Thai</a>), <em>khaam</em> (<a href="https://id.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laos">Laos </a>), <em>khoua me</em> (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cambodia">Cambodia</a>), <em>me</em >, <em>trai me</em> (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vietnam">Vietnamese</a>), and <em>tamarind</em> (< a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/English_language">English</a>). Fruit that is old, very ripe and dried is usually called <strong>asem kawak</strong>.</p>
    <p>Sour” is the general name used for all spices with <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sour">sour</a> in cooking, including <a href="https ://id.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asam_kandis">acid kandis</a> and <a href="https://id.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asam_gelugur">asam gelugur</a>. The name "tamarind" is used by the Malays because it is used in Javanese cuisine. This plant itself was imported by people from India. The names <em>Tamarindus</em> and <em>tamarind</em> are derived from <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arabic_Language">Arabic</a> الهندي <em >tamrul-hindī</em>. It means roughly: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kurma">dates</a> <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/India">India </a>. Tamarind originally came from the black continent, Africa. But in India, this plant is used as a productive plant and full of benefits. For this reason, this plant is called Indian dates, considering the flesh of the fruit is like dates</p>
    <p>Javanese tamarind is a plant <a href="https://id.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tropics">tropical</a>. Its origin is thought to be from <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Savana">savanna</a> <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Afrika"> East Africa</a> where wild species are found, one of which is <a href="https://id.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sudan">Sudan</a>. For thousands of years, this plant has ventured into tropical <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asia">Asia</a>, and then also to <a href="https://en .wikipedia.org/wiki/Caribbean">Caribbean</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latin_America">Latin America</a>. In many appropriate places, including <a href="https://id.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indonesia">Indonesia</a>, this plant is partly wild as in <a href="https://id .wikipedia.org/wiki/Hutan_gugur_daun_tropica">deciduous forests</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Savanna">savanna</a>.</p>
        <p>The tamarind tree can grow well up to a height of about 1,000 m (sometimes up to 1,500 m) above sea level, on sandy or clay soil, especially in areas with a clear and long dry season. In addition to the flesh of the fruit, many parts of the tamarind tree can be used as ingredients for traditional <a href="https://id.wikipedia.org/wiki/Obat_traditional">medicine</a>. The young leaves (Jw. <em>sinom</em>) are used with <a href="https://id.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kunyit">turmeric</a> and other ingredients to make traditional Javanese herbal medicine namely jamu sinom for a refreshing drink, jamu gepyok is drunk to promote and increase breast milk and can also be used as a poultice (applied to or applied to the surface of the skin) to reduce inflammation and pain in the joints, above wound or in pain <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rheumatism">rheumatism</a>. The young leaves are boiled to treat coughs and fever. The ground bark is used to heal wounds, ulcers, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bullet">boils</a> and rashes. Tamarind bark is also used as <a href="https://centerproductherbal.net/obat-strong-klg-pill.html%7Try">strong</a><sup>[<em><a href="https ://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:dead_links">permanently disabled links</a></em>]</sup>. Flour seeds to treat <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dysentry">dysentery</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diarrhea"> diarrhea</a>. Tamarind leaves are febrifuge, analgesic, and antiseptic. The bark is astringent and tonic. Then, the fruit is laxative, antipyretic, antiseptic, abortivum, and</p>',
    'ttl3' => 'September 29 2021',
    /* Artikel No 4 */
    'isi4' => '<p>Tamarind is commonly used as a mixture of cooking spices in many dishes as a flavoring or a sour taste enhancer in food. For example, in tamarind vegetables or sometimes in pempek sauce, fruit salad seasoning, pecel seasoning, tamarind fried chili sauce, tamarind candy, Javanese tamarind drink, tamarind ice and others.</p>
    <p>But who would have thought that in addition to tamarind food ingredients, it can also be made for candy, namely sweet and sour sugar candy, sweet and sour sugar candy is an ancient snack made from tamarind basic ingredients, the shape of this sweet and sour sugar candy is round. small brownish black color, and all over the surface sprinkled with sugar.</p>
    <p>Javanese tamarind candy has a sweet and sour taste that is produced from granulated sugar. So this candied candy also looks very distinctive when compared to other types of candy in general, which has a smooth surface texture, while the surface for sour candy looks rough because of the sprinkling of sugar. </p>
    <p>Here are the ingredients and how to make sour candy as reported from www.hypermart.co.id</p>
    <p>B<strong>ahan:</strong></p>
    <ul><li>250 gr tamarind</li><li>500 gr bread flour</li><li>250 gr brown sugar</li><li>500 gr granulated sugar</li></ul >
    <p><strong>How to make:</strong></p>
    <ol type="1"><li>Put the tamarind in a plastic bowl, add about 2 cups of water, separate from the seeds.</li><li>After separating from the seeds, dissolve, strain and set aside.</li ><li>Slice the brown sugar until smooth, put it in 2 cups of boiling water.</li><li>After the brown sugar dissolves, add the tamarind solution.</li><li>After boiling, reduce the heat and let it simmer for approx. 30 minutes or until the water is reduced, strain again.</li><li>With a low heat, put the dough back into the mixture while continuing to stir. Add the bread flour little by little while stirring with a wooden stirrer, stirring until smooth.</li><li>Turn off the heat, let it cool. Once cool, form the dough into small balls.</li><li>Prepare the granulated sugar on a wide plate, roll the tamarind ball over it until the sugar is evenly distributed.<br></li></ol>
    <p>Good luck…</p>',
