    'isi17' => '<h6>Javanese acid</h6>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;"><a href="https://asamjawagunung.com">Javanese tamarind</a> also known as tamarind or tamarind is a fruit that has a distinctive sour taste. , commonly grown and traded for use as a spice in Indonesian cuisine. The plants are traded as a flavoring or a sour taste enhancer in food, for example in sour vegetables or sometimes pempek sauce. Tamarind is produced by a tree with the scientific name Tamarindus indica, belonging to the Fabaceae (Leguminosae) tribe. This species is the only member of the genus Tamarindus. Fruit that is old, very ripe and dried is usually called tamarind kawak.</p>
    <p><span id="more-557"></span></p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">The tamarind tree is large, evergreen (not experiencing leaf fall), up to 30 m high and up to 2 m diameter at the base. Bark grayish brown, rough and split, vertical grooves. The canopy is shady and densely leafy, wide and rounded.</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">Even pinnate compound leaves, 5-13 cm long, alternately located, with tapering ribbon-like supporting leaves, pinkish-white. Leaves oval narrowed, 8-16 pairs, each measuring 0.5-1 × 1-3.5 cm, flat-edged, slanted and rounded base, rounded tip to slightly curved.</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">Flowers are arranged in loose bunches, in leaf axils or at the tips of twigs, up to 16 cm long. Butterfly flower with 4 petals and 5 petals, smells good. Crown whitish yellow with red-brown veins, up to 1.5 cm. when very ripe, sweet and sour and sticky. Dark brown beans, shiny and hard, slightly square.</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;"><a href="https://asamjawagunung.com/value-gizi-asam-jawa/">tamarind fruit</a> including fruit single true fruit (real fruit), dry, and containing more than one seed. Tamarind fruit box and classified in the pods (Legumen). The fruit is 5-15 cm long, 2.5 cm thick, slightly curved and wraps around the seeds. The outer shell of tamarind is soft and the flesh is sour. In each pod there are 1-10 seeds wrapped in a sticky pulp
    <h6>Classification of Tamarind</h6>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">Kingdom : Plantae</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">Subkingdom : Tracheobionta (vessel)</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">Superdivisio : Spermatophyta (producing seeds)</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">Divisio : Magnoliophyta (flowering)</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">Class : Magnoliopsida (dicotyledonous)</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">Sub-class : Rosidae</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">Ordo : Fabales</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">Family : Fabaceae (legumes)</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">Genus : Tamarindus</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">Species : Tamarindus indica L</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;"><a href="https://asamjawagunung.com/jual-produk-asam-jawa-gunung/jual-asam-jawa-gunung-kuning -10-kg/">Javanese tamarind (Tamarindus indica)</a> belongs to the Fabaceae (Leguminosae) tribe. This species is the only member of the genus Tamarindus. Some parts of the tamarind plant have been used for food and medical purposes. Tamarind fruit flesh is used as raw material for making herbal medicines, while tamarind flowers and leaves are commonly consumed as vegetables.</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;"> Tamarind seed extract contains natural polysaccharides and tannins consisting of D-galactose, D-7 glucose and D-silose which are natural flocculants. Tannins are phenolic compounds that are soluble in water and can precipitate proteins from solution. Natural coagulants, especially polysaccharides, are more environmentally friendly when compared to organic and inorganic coagulants.</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">The tamarind seeds are irregular in shape, dark brown or glossy black in color. Seeds are divided into three main parts, namely the seed coat (Spermodermis), the umbilical cord (Funiculus), and the seed core (Nukleus seminis). The seed coat consists of an outer layer, a middle layer and an inner skin layer. The core of tamarind seeds consists of an embryo (embryo) and an embryo (albumen) which is a food reserve network for the beginning of growth.</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;"> Tamarind Seeds Tamarind seeds can be used as a coagulant in the coagulation process because of the consideration of the tannin content in the seeds. Tannins are phenolic compounds that are soluble in water. With a molecular weight between 500-3000 can precipitate proteins from solution. Most tamarind seeds contain tannins, especially in the seed coat. The darker the color of the seed coat, the higher the tannin content. Tannins contained in plants are active substances that cause the coagulation process and natural polymers such as starch function as flocculants and coagulants.</p>
    <h6>Javanese Acid Content</h6>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">Compounds Contained in Tamarind Seeds Tamarind seeds contain active substances in the form of tannins, essential oils and several natural polymers such as starch, gum and albuminoids.</p> p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">A. Tannins</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">Tannins are compounds that can inhibit microbial growth by inhibiting the work of enzymes such as cellulose, pectinase, oxidative peroxide and others. The phenol present in the tannin compound is known as carbolic acid which in high concentrations can be toxic to bacteria and is usually used to kill germs.</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">B. Essential Oil</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">Essential oil (aromatic oil) is a group of vegetable oils that are thick liquid and at room temperature will easily evaporate so that it will cause a distinctive aroma. This oil is used to reduce unpleasant odors.</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">C. Pati</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">Starch is a glucose polymer which has granules (granules) and has a diameter of 2 microns-100 microns which is composed of straight polymer components (amylose) which make up approximately 25% starch and branched polymer (amylopectin).</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">D. sap</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">Sap is a hydroxy carbon polymer compound produced from colloids. Hydrocarbon compounds are chemical compounds that contain only carbon (C) and hydrogen (H). The sap is used as a thickener, binder, emulsifier, stabilizer, adhesive, coagulant and as a filter in the textile industry.</p>
    <h6><a href="https://asamjawagunung.com/jenang-asam-jawa-yang-menggiurkan/">Javanese acid</a> as medicine</h6>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">Javanese tamarind can be used as an ingredient to treat various diseases, including Asthma, Cough, Fever, Heat Pain, Rheumatism, Stomachache, Morbili; Allergies / hives, canker sores, new wounds, ulcers, eczema, boils; Swelling from centipede/bee stings, Snake bites, Hair loss.</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">1. Asthma Ingredients:</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">2 pieces of tamarind tree bark, fennel pulawaras to taste How to make: both ingredients are boiled with 1 liter of water until boiling, then filtered. How to use: drink 2 times a day</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">2. Dry Cough</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">Ingredient: 3 tamarind fruit pods, handful of saga leaves Method: Both ingredients are boiled in 4 cups of water until only 1 cup is left and then filtered. use: drink 2 times a day, morning and evening</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">3. Fever Ingredients: 1 handful of tamarind leaves, fennel pulawaras to taste; How to make: both ingredients are boiled with liter of water until it boils, then filtered How to use: drink 2 times a day, morning and evening</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">4. Hot Pain Ingredients: 2 ripe tamarind fruit pods, salt to taste How to make: both ingredients are brewed with 1 cup hot water, then filtered How to use: drink normally Note: pregnant women should not drink this recipe</p>
    <p class="western" style="text-align: left;">5. Rheumatism Ingredients: 1 handful of tamarind leaves, 2-3 seeds of tamarind (klungsu = java) How to make: both ingredients are finely ground How to use: used to compress the sore part</p>',
